{
    "analysis": "From the prior Executor run we confirmed all four CSVs were loaded and summarized. Key observations: metric.csv is large (~29,675 rows) with many Tomcat04 KPI groups (many groups have 31 rows). trace.csv and log.csv also contain many groups with 31 rows. error_logs.csv contains 0 rows. We have not yet computed global thresholds for all component-KPI series restricted to the candidate root-cause components, nor have we filtered metric points to the incident window (March 25, 2021 00:00 to 00:30). To follow the required workflow (threshold calculation -> data extraction -> metric analysis -> trace analysis -> log analysis) we must next: (1) compute global thresholds (P95 and P5) per component-KPI across the full available series (for only the possible root-cause components), and (2) extract metric rows within the incident window and detect anomalies relative to those thresholds. This will narrow candidate faulty component-KPIs and the earliest anomaly times to investigate with traces/logs. No root cause is concluded yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using cached metric.csv, compute global thresholds for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair where cmdb_id is in the provided possible root-cause component list [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat04, Tomcat03, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02]. For each such pair calculate: (a) count of full-series points, (b) global P95 of 'value', (c) global P5 of 'value'. Cache this threshold table in the kernel.\n\nThen filter metric.csv to the incident window March 25, 2021 00:00 to 00:30 (UTC+8) and keep only rows for the same candidate components. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) in that window compute compact anomaly aggregates: (1) count_exceed_p95 = number of points in window with value >= global P95; (2) earliest_exceed_ts = earliest timestamp in window where value >= P95 (NULL if none); (3) max_value_in_window; (4) count_below_p5 = number of points in window with value <= global P5; (5) earliest_below_ts = earliest timestamp where value <= P5 (NULL if none); (6) min_value_in_window.\n\nReturn a compact table limited to top 20 rows sorted by (count_exceed_p95 + count_below_p5) descending, showing columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count_full_series, p95_value, p5_value, count_exceed_p95, earliest_exceed_ts, max_value_in_window, count_below_p5, earliest_below_ts, min_value_in_window. Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) groups examined and cache both the threshold table and the filtered-incident-window metric table in kernel variables for subsequent steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous Executor run loaded and summarized files but failed to compute global thresholds and filter the incident-window metrics. We need to compute global thresholds (P95 and P5) per component-KPI for only the allowed candidate components before extracting incident-window anomalies. This step will produce a compact threshold table to be cached for the next, simpler filtering step.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv (use cached table if available). Restrict rows to cmdb_id in the candidate list: [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat04, Tomcat03, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02]. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair compute: (a) count of all series points, (b) global P95 of value, (c) global P5 of value. Return a compact table limited to top 20 groups sorted by count descending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count_full_series, p95_value, p5_value. Cache the full threshold table in kernel variable named thresholds_df for later steps. Do not filter by incident window in this step."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous Executor runs we have: (1) global thresholds (P95/P5) per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) for candidate components cached in thresholds_df; (2) the incident-window filtered metrics cached in metrics_incident_df; (3) a compact anomalies table metric_anomalies_df showing for each group counts of points meeting >=P95 and <=P5, earliest timestamps, and min/max in the window. Many groups show count_exceed_p95 = 31 and count_below_p5 = 31 with p95 == p5 == observed value, indicating constant series where thresholds equal observed values (these are not informative faults). We still need to identify real faults: groups that show significant deviations from their global thresholds (e.g., >50% breach) and find the earliest timestamp when that deviation first occurred. This will narrow candidate faulty component-KPIs for subsequent trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using cached metric_anomalies_df and metrics_incident_df, identify candidate faulty groups with meaningful severity. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) in metric_anomalies_df compute two severity scores:\n1) up_severity = (max_value_in_window - p95_value) / max(abs(p95_value), 1e-9)\n2) down_severity = (p5_value - min_value_in_window) / max(abs(p5_value), 1e-9)\nSelect groups where either up_severity > 0.5 or down_severity > 0.5 (i.e., breach >50%). For each selected group find the earliest timestamp in metrics_incident_df where the breach first occurs (value >= p95_value for up breaches; value <= p5_value for down breaches). Return a compact table limited to top 20 groups sorted by max(up_severity, down_severity) descending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count_full_series, p95_value, p5_value, up_severity, down_severity, breach_type (UP or DOWN), earliest_breach_ts, earliest_breach_value. Also return the total number of candidate groups found and cache this result as severe_metric_candidates_df for the next step. Keep outputs compact (no raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step produced severe_metric_candidates_df with 104 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) groups that breach global thresholds by more than 50%. Most breaches are UP (values above P95). Many breaches start exactly at 1616601600 (2021-03-25 00:00:00 UTC+8), indicating anomalies present at the start of the incident window. Top severity groups include Mysql01 (very large relative breaches because p95/p5 == 0), MG01/MG02 (OS-level disk/CPU/wait metrics), Tomcat nodes, and a Redis02 CPU WIO breach appearing at 00:01:00. We need to localize two separate failures in the 00:00–00:30 window. To choose candidate root-cause components for those two failures, we should first aggregate the severe candidates by component to see which components have many distinct severe KPIs (indicating a node-level problem) and capture earliest breach times per component (to split events by occurrence time). This will let us pick a small set of components to investigate further with traces and logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the cached severe_metric_candidates_df, produce a compact per-component summary and cache it as severe_by_component_df. Specifically:\n1) Group severe_metric_candidates_df by cmdb_id and compute: (a) severe_kpi_count = number of distinct kpi_name in the group, (b) max_severity = maximum of max(up_severity, down_severity) for the group's KPIs, (c) earliest_breach_ts = minimum earliest_breach_ts across the group's KPIs, (d) example_kpis = a comma-separated string of up to 5 distinct kpi_name examples for that component (prefer the highest-severity KPIs first).\n2) Return a compact table limited to top 20 rows sorted by severe_kpi_count descending. Show columns: cmdb_id, severe_kpi_count, max_severity, earliest_breach_ts, example_kpis.\n3) Also return the total number of distinct components found and cache the result as severe_by_component_df for the next step.\nKeep the output compact (no raw timeseries) and do not convert timestamps to datetimes."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace-level anomaly detection shows many IG01 trace features (row_count and duration variants) exceeding global P95 with earliest exceedances at 1616601600 and 1616601660. Metric analysis produced 104 severe metric candidates aggregated into components: MG01 (12 KPIs), MG02 (11), Tomcat04 (11), Mysql01/02 (10 each), Tomcat01 (10), Tomcat02/03, Redis02, IG01/IG02, etc. Many metric breaches begin at 1616601600 (2021-03-25 00:00:00 UTC+8); some trace exceedances start at 1616601660 (00:01:00) as well. According to the localization rules, when multiple service-level components are faulty we should use traces to pick the most downstream faulty service in the call chain. To identify the two distinct failures (their root cause component, exact occurrence time, and reason), we need to map trace anomalies into communication pairs (origin ↔ destination) and intersect those pairs with the set of components that show severe metrics. This will show which downstream services in anomalous call paths are themselves metric-faulty and have earliest breach timestamps, allowing us to pick root-cause components per failure. Currently we have trace_anomalies_df, traces_incident_df, severe_metric_candidates_df, and severe_by_component_df cached; we need a compact table of trace communication pairs involving severe components to proceed.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using cached trace_anomalies_df and severe_by_component_df, extract communication pairs from trace_name and find trace anomalies that involve severe components: \n1) For each row in trace_anomalies_df where trace_name contains the substring 'to_' or 'from_', parse the counterpart component name (e.g., 'trace.to_Tomcat03.row_count' → dest='Tomcat03'; 'trace.from_IG01.row_count' → src='IG01'). Create columns: origin_cmdb = cmdb_id, counterpart_cmdb = parsed name, direction = 'TO' or 'FROM' (based on 'to_' or 'from_').\n2) Keep only rows where either origin_cmdb or counterpart_cmdb appears in the severe_by_component_df.cmdb_id list (i.e., involves a severe component). For each kept row compute these compact fields: origin_cmdb, counterpart_cmdb, direction, trace_name, count_full_series, p95_value, count_exceed_p95, earliest_exceed_ts, max_value_in_window.\n3) Return a compact table limited to top 20 rows sorted first by count_exceed_p95 descending then by earliest_exceed_ts ascending. Also return a small aggregate summary: counts of such anomalous trace pairs per counterpart_cmdb (top 10) and per origin_cmdb (top 10). Cache the resulting pairs table as trace_pairs_df for the next step. Keep outputs compact; do not return full time series or convert timestamps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric and trace anomaly detection and built compact diagnostics per component. Findings so far: many components show severe UP breaches beginning at 1616601600 (2021-03-25 00:00:00 UTC+8) or 1616601660 (00:01:00). Components cluster into two timing groups: an early group (earliest breach 1616601600) including MG01, MG02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, Mysql01, and a slightly later group (earliest breach 1616601660) including IG01, IG02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Mysql02, Redis02. Per the localization rules, node-level faults may represent distinct failures; where multiple service-level faults exist in a trace, the most downstream faulty service is likely the root cause. To assign two concrete failures we must validate evidence for candidate root components across metrics and traces. The strongest candidates to represent two separate failures are: (A) MG01 (many disk/CPU/network severe KPIs, earliest 1616601600) representing a node-level resource issue at the window start; (B) IG01 (trace anomalies with Tomcat03 and its own severe KPIs, earliest 1616601660) representing an inter-service request degradation visible at ~00:01. Before finalizing, we should fetch concise evidence records to confirm each: for each candidate component, list its top severe KPIs (severity, earliest breach ts/value, max value) and for IG01 also show the related anomalous trace pairs (e.g., IG01→Tomcat03) with earliest_exceed_ts and counts so we can verify that the most downstream faulty service in those call chains is indeed faulty and the correct occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Produce compact evidence for two candidate root components MG01 and IG01 using cached tables (severe_metric_candidates_df and trace_pairs_df):\n1) For MG01: return up to top 10 severe KPI rows for MG01 sorted by severity (max(up_severity, down_severity) desc). For each row show: kpi_name, breach_type, severity, earliest_breach_ts, earliest_breach_value, max_value_in_window. Also return the component-level earliest_breach_ts and severe_kpi_count (from component_diagnostics_df) for MG01.\n2) For IG01: return up to top 10 severe KPI rows for IG01 with the same columns as above. Also return the component-level earliest_breach_ts and severe_kpi_count for IG01.\n3) Additionally, return all trace_pairs_df rows where origin_cmdb == 'IG01' or counterpart_cmdb == 'IG01' (limit to top 20 rows) showing: origin_cmdb, counterpart_cmdb, direction, trace_name, count_full_series, p95_value, count_exceed_p95, earliest_exceed_ts, max_value_in_window.\nKeep all outputs compact and bounded (MG01 KPIs ≤10 rows, IG01 KPIs ≤10 rows, trace pairs ≤20 rows). Cache these returned tables as mg01_evidence_df, ig01_evidence_df, and ig01_trace_pairs_df for the final localization step."
}

